William Gosse (ca.1813 &ndash; 21 July 1883) married Agnes Grant (ca.1811 &ndash; 18 June 1891). Their family included:
*Agnes Grant Gosse (1837–1909) married [[Alexander Hay (South Australian politician)|Alexander Hay]] (1820 &ndash; 1898) on 13 March 1872. She was the author of ''After-Glow Memories'' (1905), ''Malcolm Canmore's Pearl'' (1907), ''Archibald Menzies'' (1908) and ''Footprints: A Memoir of the Late Alexander Hay'' (1899).<ref>Wilde, William H.; Hooton, Joy; and Andrews, Barry (eds.) ''The Oxford Companion to Australian Literature'' 2nd ed. Oxford University Press 1994 ISBN 0 19 553381 X</ref> She and her daughter Helen died with the sinking of the [[SS Waratah|SS ''Waratah'']], just a year after their mansion "[[Mount Breckan House]]" was destroyed by fire.
*Mary (ca.1838 &ndash; 1 February 1924) married Alexander "Alick" Melville ( &ndash; 16 October 1871) on 7 December 1859
*David Grant Gosse (ca.1841 &ndash; 1 July 1880) married Emily Sarah Fenn ( &ndash; ca.11 August 1896) on 8 April 1869
*[[William Christie Gosse]] (11 December 1842 &ndash; 12 August 1881), the noted explorer, married Gertrude Ritchie ( &ndash; 10 May 1869 at Robe) on 8 December 1868. He married again, to step-niece Agnes "Aggie" Hay (7 July 1854 &ndash; 27 October 1933), a daughter of brother-in-law Alexander Hay by his first wife, on 22 December 1874
