Their home from 1854 was on King William Street; from 1858 in Grenfell Street, from 1862 on North Terrace, and from 1880 on Wakefield Street, Kent Town.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article45788867 |title=Out Among The By vox People. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1931 - 1954)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=31 October 1951 |accessdate=25 May 2012 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Recognition==
The Gosse Wing of the [[Julia Farr Centre|Home for Incurables]] was named in his honour, and opened by his son Charles in 1884.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43808790 |title=The Home for Incurables |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|South Australian Register (Adelaide, SA : 1839 - 1900)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=18 October 1884 |accessdate=24 May 2012 |page=1 Supplement: Supplement to the South Australian Register |publisher=National Library of Australia}} <br>This reference has much detail on the foundation and operation of the centre.</ref>

